04642nam a22006495i 9781503603189DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202017cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2016055465  a97815036031897 a10.1515/97815036031892doi  a(DE-B1597)563865  a(OCoLC)1178769430  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aDS113.7b.N378 2017 4aDS113.7b.N378 2017 7aHIS0190002bisacsh04a305.8992/74056942231 aNassar, Maha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBrothers Apart :bPalestinian Citizens of Israel and the Arab World /cMaha Nassar. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Middle Eastern and Islamic Societies and Cultures00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. STRATEGIES OF RESISTANCE -- t2. COMPETING NARRATIVES -- t3. DEBATES ON DECOLONIZATION -- t4. PALESTINIAN SPOKESMEN -- t5. COMPLICATED HEROES -- tCONCLUSION -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen the state of Israel was established in 1948, not all Palestinians became refugees: some stayed behind and were soon granted citizenship. Those who remained, however, were relegated to second-class status in this new country, controlled by a military regime that restricted their movement and political expression. For two decades, Palestinian citizens of Israel were cut off from friends and relatives on the other side of the Green Line, as well as from the broader Arab world. Yet they were not passive in the face of this profound isolation. Palestinian intellectuals, party organizers, and cultural producers in Israel turned to the written word. Through writers like Mahmoud Darwish and Samih al-Qasim, poetry, journalism, fiction, and nonfiction became sites of resistance and connection alike. With this book, Maha Nassar examines their well-known poetry and uncovers prose works that have, until now, been largely overlooked. The writings of Palestinians in Israel played a key role in fostering a shared national consciousness and would become a central means of alerting Arabs in the region to the conditions-and to the defiance-of these isolated Palestinians. Brothers Apart is the first book to reveal how Palestinian intellectuals forged transnational connections through written texts and engaged with contemporaneous decolonization movements throughout the Arab world, challenging both Israeli policies and their own cultural isolation. Maha Nassar reexamines these intellectuals as the subjects, not objects, of their own history and brings to life their perspectives on a fraught political environment. Her readings not only deprovincialize the Palestinians of Israel, but write them back into Palestinian, Arab, and global history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aPalestinian ArabszIsraelxEthnic identityxHistoryy20th century. 0aPalestinian ArabszIsraelxEthnic identity. 0aPalestinian ArabszIsraelxIntellectual lifey20th century. 0aPalestinian ArabszIsraelxSocial conditions. 0aPolitics and literaturezPalestinexHistoryy20th century. 4aPalestinian intellectuals. 4acultural decolonization. 4apolitical isolation. 4apolitical vocabularies. 4atextual production. 4atransnational. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Israel & Palestine.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360318940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503603189423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503603189.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGru